AGI - A hundred days after the opening of Paris 2024, the cost of the Olympic Games crystallizes the interest of the French media. If, on the one hand, the initial budget of 6.8 billion euros has been exceeded, on the other with 8.8 billion already spent, the Paris edition of the Olympic Games should be one of the least expensive since 1988. The conditional is of obligation because, in order to know with precision the total cost of the maxi international sporting event, the final report of the Court of Auditors will be expected not before autumn 2025.
&nbsp;
According to a note published by the consulting firm Asteres, the cost of the organization of Paris 2024 should be at the end of €11.8 billion. Also according to the same source, will be the cheapest thirds of the last 36 years. Moreover, in recent history, no Olympic budget has respected the budget, so, from this point of view, Paris has failed to do better than its predecessors.
&nbsp;
Among the last examples mentioned by the French press, there are the Tokyo Games, affected by the aggravation of the health crisis Covid-19 and their postponement of one year: According to the Japanese Court of Auditors cost 12 billion euros, almost twice as much as the estimate at the time of application. London, according to estimates, cost between 12 and 15 billion euros. In Beijing, in 2008, the account exploded, mainly due to the cost of infrastructure. In Athens, in 2004, the Olympic Games cost €13 billion, adding to the Greek government deficit.
&nbsp;
The budget already spent for the Paris 2024 Games, divided between the Organizing Committee of the Olympic Games (COJO) and the Sociètè de livraison des ouvrages olympiques (Solideo), was 8.8 billion euros, two billion more than the 6.8 billion planned in 2019. Initially, the Organizing Committee's budget was 3.8 billion euros, more than 3.2 billion euros in the application dossier. At the end of 2021, the budget for the organization of the Games was 3,98 billion euros. A year later, at the end of 2022, it had risen to 4.38 billion euros, with an increase of 10% due to inflation.
&nbsp;
As a reminder, the COJO is based on private funds from sponsors (1.24 billion), the International Olympic Committee (1.2 billion) and the sale of tickets (1.4 billion). As regards infrastructure, it has always been expected that public finances were borne: It is the Olympic Village, which will be transformed into houses to be put on the market (646 million euros, of which 542 million from the State), the catwalk between the Stade de France and the Olympic water center, the new pools of Seine-Saint-Denis.
&nbsp;
Through the Sociètè de livraison des ouvrages olympiques (Solideo), which has a total budget of 4,4 billion euros, almost 1,8 billion euros of public money - between State, region Ile de France, Paris, Seine-Saint-Denis - were destined to the Olympics. Other expenses not yet quantified, will be made known after the Games. Pierre Moscovici, President of the French Court of Auditors, had estimated the final public investment in three billion euros. "Three, four or five billion euros. You will know after the Games," Moscovici has recently specified.
&nbsp;
"There is no reason why it should be five billion," said Sport Minister Amèlie Oudèa-Castèra, who insisted that there are no "budget or hidden costs". A report by the French Court of Auditors, scheduled for autumn 2025, will officially and transparently respond to all these estimates and speculations on the cost of Paris 2024.&nbsp;

