AGI - Russian bombings have caused at least 17 deaths and dozens of wounded in the northern city of Chernihiv>, an attack that President Volodymyr Zelensky > said could have been avoided if he had received sufficient anti-aircraft defenses. Dmitro Brijinski reported that 13 people were killed and 61 wounds, including two children. In a preliminary report, Interior Minister Igor Klimenko warned that the budget could increase because there are missing persons and rescues continue to try to extract people from under the rubble. Subsequently the Ukrainian agency Ukrinform updated the budget to 17 victims. The Russians attacked Chernihiv with three Iskander missiles. >
&nbsp;
A Ukrainian attack with drones> instead targeted a Tupolev aircraft factory in the Russian Tatarstan.> The goal was the factory where Moscow produces and repairs Tu-22M and Tu-160M bombers. They told RBC-Ukraine sources of secret services, according to which the anti-aircraft sirens played in the area of the Gorbunov plant in Kazan. At the same time, personnel evacuation began. Rosaviatsia, the Russian federal agency for air transport, has announced that the traffic at the airports of Kazan, Nizhnyokamsk and Nizhny Novgorod is suspended. Photos and videos of explosions in the plant began to circulate on the Internet.
&nbsp;
More than 50 thousand Russian soldiers died from the beginning of the invasion of Ukraine > in February 2022 according to a count made by the service in the Russian language of the BBC and the Russian site Mediazona >. The calculation, published after a joint research and completed on 7 April 2024, is based on several sources of information, such as official press releases, news of press and on social networks or visits to cemeteries. Neither Ukraine nor Russia have published official reports of losses from the beginning of the war, so both media warn that their count does not intend to be exhaustive. At the end of February, Ukraine estimated the number of its dead soldiers in 31,000, while the Russian army never reported its military losses.
&nbsp;
The Kremlin spokesman Dmitri Peskov used the "law on State Secret" and the "special case" of the Russian invasion of Ukraine to justify the absence of official communications on the military losses of the Moscow army. Last August, the New York Times, citing US officials, estimated Russian military losses in 120,000. On 29 January, in a written response to a MP, British Defence Minister James Heappey estimated the number of Russian soldiers killed or wounded.
&nbsp;
BBC Russian and Mediazona have dedicated much of their reconstruction to the fate of Russian prisoners recruited to fight the front: tens of thousands of prisoners were recruited by Russian prisons in exchange for the release promise, according to the two media. According to the survey of the two media, on a sample of over 1,000 prisoners, half of those recruited by the Russian army would have died two months after being sent to the front. Those recruited by the paramilitary group Wagner generally died three months after their enlistment. The two media also emphasised that in the second year of conflict more than 27,300 Russian soldiers died "which illustrates the enormous human cost of territorial conquests" obtained by the army sent by the government of Valdimir Putin.

