AGI - In Croatia began voting for parliamentary elections after an intense campaign between a prime minister looking for a new mandate and a populist president who wants to become head of the government. The seats were opened at 7 p.m. until 7 p.m. The reckoning between Conservative Premier Andrej Plenkovic and President Zoran Milanovic, a leftist, arrives while the country struggles against corruption, shortage of labour, the highest rate of inflation in the Eurozone > and illegal immigration. For months, Plenkovic and the Croatian Democratic Union (HDZ) in power seemed ready to put the menes without difficulty on the third term as head of the government, but in mid-March Milanvic made the shocking announcement that he would be the candidate of the SDP Social-Democrats. Milanvic was Prime Minister shortly before Plenkovic and his role as President is largely ceremonial. "Croatian never had such a corrupt government," he said, in his final rally.
&nbsp;
Defining the elections a "referendum on the future of the country" urged citizens to "go to vote for anyone except for HDZ". Milanovic called Plenkovic the "crime father" > and cited, for example, the recent appointment of the new head prosecutor of the country, a judge with alleged ties with suspects of corruption. Corruption has long been a problem for HDZ. Many ministers of Plenkovic resigned because under investigation and the anti-corruption struggle was fundamental for EU membership in 2013. According to a ruling from the Supreme Court, Milanvic could have run for election only if he had previously resigned from the office of president and Plenkovic - who has been Premier since 2016 - accused him of violating the constitution, of making speeches of hate incitement and defined him as a "coward" for not resigning himself as well as for his criticism of the support of the EU to Ukraine against the Russian invasion.
&nbsp;
"Milanovic pushes Croatia and the Croatian people into the Russian world," Plenkovic> said during a demonstration. For his part, the President argued that his only interest is to protect Croatian interests and prevent the country from being "broken into war". The president is at the top of the polls on political popularity and his entry into the election campaign strengthened the SDP. But no party should get the absolute majority in the assembly from 151 seats, according to the polls that give the HDZ 30% of the votes, followed by the SDP with 20%, while the right nationalist movement will be in all probability the needle of the balance in the formation of a new government.
&nbsp;
HDZ has dominated Croatian governments since the country's independence from Yugoslavia in 1991, while SDP was the pillar of opposition. Milanvic, who has been Prime Minister from 2011 to 2016, is known for his phoeasant rhetoric and swearing words in the invectives against HDZ opponents, EU officials and its critics. His mandate expires in January, but he said that he will resign if the SDP and its allies will get the majority to form a new government.&nbsp;

